## shadcn/ui Component Guidelines

### Component Selection Philosophy
shadcn/ui provides beautifully designed, accessible components. Use them as your foundation and customize only when necessary.

### Core Components & Usage

#### 1. **Button Component**
```tsx
// Primary action - high contrast
<Button>Primary Action</Button>

// Secondary action - lower contrast
<Button variant="secondary">Secondary Action</Button>

// Destructive action - use sparingly
<Button variant="destructive">Delete</Button>

// Ghost/minimal for tertiary actions
<Button variant="ghost">Cancel</Button>

// Outline for secondary prominence
<Button variant="outline">Learn More</Button>
```

**Button Best Practices:**
- One primary action per screen/section
- Use size variants: `sm`, `default`, `lg`
- Add icons with `lucide-react` for clarity
- Destructive actions should require confirmation

#### 2. **Card Component**
```tsx
<Card>
  <CardHeader>
    <CardTitle>Treatment Plan</CardTitle>
    <CardDescription>Review and approve recommendations</CardDescription>
  </CardHeader>
  <CardContent>
    {/* Main content */}
  </CardContent>
  <CardFooter>
    {/* Actions */}
  </CardFooter>
</Card>
```

**Card Best Practices:**
- Use cards to group related information
- Consistent padding within cards
- Avoid nesting cards too deeply
- Use CardDescription for context

#### 3. **Form Components**
```tsx
<Form>
  <FormField>
    <FormLabel>Patient Name</FormLabel>
    <FormControl>
      <Input placeholder="Enter patient name" />
    </FormControl>
    <FormDescription>Patient's full legal name</FormDescription>
    <FormMessage /> {/* Error messages */}
  </FormField>
</Form>
```

**Form Best Practices:**
- Always provide labels
- Use FormDescription for helpful hints
- Show FormMessage for validation errors
- Use appropriate input types (email, tel, number)
- Group related fields together
- Use proper HTML semantics

#### 4. **Dialog/Modal Component**
```tsx
<Dialog>
  <DialogTrigger asChild>
    <Button>Open Dialog</Button>
  </DialogTrigger>
  <DialogContent>
    <DialogHeader>
      <DialogTitle>Confirm Action</DialogTitle>
      <DialogDescription>This action cannot be undone.</DialogDescription>
    </DialogHeader>
    {/* Content */}
    <DialogFooter>
      <Button variant="outline">Cancel</Button>
      <Button>Confirm</Button>
    </DialogFooter>
  </DialogContent>
</Dialog>
```

**Dialog Best Practices:**
- Use for critical actions requiring focus
- Always provide DialogDescription for context
- Primary action on the right, cancel on the left
- Destructive actions require explicit confirmation
- Keep content focused and brief

#### 5. **Alert Component**
```tsx
// Info alert
<Alert>
  <AlertTitle>Information</AlertTitle>
  <AlertDescription>Additional context for users.</AlertDescription>
</Alert>

// Destructive/warning alert
<Alert variant="destructive">
  <AlertTitle>Critical Risk Detected</AlertTitle>
  <AlertDescription>Drug interaction identified.</AlertDescription>
</Alert>
```

**Alert Best Practices:**
- Use for important system messages
- Always include both title and description
- Use destructive variant for critical warnings
- Position prominently when critical

#### 6. **Badge Component**
```tsx
<Badge>Low Risk</Badge>
<Badge variant="secondary">Medium Risk</Badge>
<Badge variant="destructive">High Risk</Badge>
<Badge variant="outline">Status</Badge>
```

**Badge Best Practices:**
- Use for status indicators
- Keep text short (1-2 words)
- Use semantic variants for risk levels
- Consistent placement across similar items

#### 7. **Tabs Component**
```tsx
<Tabs defaultValue="treatment">
  <TabsList>
    <TabsTrigger value="treatment">Treatment Plan</TabsTrigger>
    <TabsTrigger value="history">Patient History</TabsTrigger>
    <TabsTrigger value="notes">Clinical Notes</TabsTrigger>
  </TabsList>
  <TabsContent value="treatment">
    {/* Treatment plan content */}
  </TabsContent>
  {/* Other tab contents */}
</Tabs>
```

**Tabs Best Practices:**
- Use for related content sections
- 3-7 tabs maximum
- Short, clear tab labels
- Default to most important tab

#### 8. **Table Component**
```tsx
<Table>
  <TableHeader>
    <TableRow>
      <TableHead>Medication</TableHead>
      <TableHead>Dosage</TableHead>
      <TableHead className="text-right">Risk Level</TableHead>
    </TableRow>
  </TableHeader>
  <TableBody>
    <TableRow>
      <TableCell className="font-medium">Aspirin</TableCell>
      <TableCell>500mg</TableCell>
      <TableCell className="text-right">
        <Badge>Low</Badge>
      </TableCell>
    </TableRow>
  </TableBody>
</Table>
```

**Table Best Practices:**
- Right-align numbers
- Use font-medium for primary column
- Add hover states for interactive rows
- Consider using DataTable for complex tables with sorting/filtering

#### 9. **Toast Component**
```tsx
// Success toast
toast({
  title: "Treatment Plan Saved",
  description: "Changes have been successfully saved.",
})

// Error toast
toast({
  variant: "destructive",
  title: "Error",
  description: "Failed to save treatment plan.",
})
```

**Toast Best Practices:**
- Use for non-critical feedback
- Keep messages brief
- Auto-dismiss after 3-5 seconds
- Use destructive variant for errors

#### 10. **Separator Component**
```tsx
<Separator /> {/* Horizontal */}
<Separator orientation="vertical" /> {/* Vertical */}
```

**Separator Best Practices:**
- Use to divide content sections
- Don't overuse - whitespace often works better
- Use orientation appropriately

